              <h2>How to calculate a salary increase</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator lets you work in whichever way is easiest for
                you:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Enter your current salary and a
                  <strong>raise percentage</strong> to see your new pay.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Enter your current salary and a <strong>new salary</strong> to
                  find the raise %.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Enter your current salary and a
                  <strong>raise amount</strong> (e.g. +$2/hour) to see the
                  percentage.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>1. Raise percentage formula</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Raise %</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Raise \%} = \frac{\text{New salary} - \text{Old
                  salary}}{\text{Old salary}} \times 100 \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>Example: your salary goes from $50,000 to $55,000.</p>
              <p>
                \[ \text{Raise \%} = \frac{55{,}000 - 50{,}000}{50{,}000} \times
                100 = 10\% \]
              </p>

              <h3>2. New salary from raise percentage</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>New salary</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{New salary} = \text{Old salary} \times \left(1 +
                  \frac{\text{Raise \%}}{100}\right) \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>Example: you earn $25/hour and get a 4% raise.</p>
              <p>
                \[ \text{New rate} = 25 \times (1 + 0.04) = 26 \text{ per hour}
                \]
              </p>

              <h3>3. Raise amount from percentage</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Raise amount</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Raise amount} = \text{Old salary} \times
                  \frac{\text{Raise \%}}{100} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>Example: $60,000 salary with a 5% raise:</p>
              <p>\[ \text{Raise} = 60{,}000 \times 0.05 = 3{,}000 \]</p>
              <p>Your new salary is $63,000 per year.</p>

              <h3>4. Back pay for a retroactive raise</h3>
              <p>
                If your raise is effective from an earlier date (for example,
                from January 1 but only approved in March), you may be owed
                <strong>retroactive pay</strong> for the missed periods.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Back pay</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Back pay} = \text{Raise per period} \times
                  \text{Number of past periods} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                This calculator estimates the number of whole pay periods
                between the effective date and the paid-through date based on
                your selected pay frequency.
              </p>

              <h2>Understanding typical salary increases</h2>
              <p>
                Exact numbers vary by country, industry, and economic
                conditions, but some common patterns are:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Cost-of-living / inflation adjustments:</strong> often
                  around 2–4% in normal years.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Merit increases for solid performance:</strong>
                  roughly 3–5%.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>High performance or promotion:</strong> 5–10% or more.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Changing employers:</strong> sometimes 10–20%+
                  depending on market demand.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Use market salary data (from reputable salary surveys or job
                boards) alongside this calculator to check whether a proposed
                raise keeps you competitive.
              </p>

              <h2>How to use this calculator for negotiations</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Enter your current pay and a
                  <strong>target raise %</strong> (for example, 8%).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Review the <strong>new annual salary</strong> and
                  <strong>extra per year</strong> numbers.
                </li>
                <li>Compare that to market data for your role and location.</li>
                <li>
                  Adjust the percentage until you find a realistic but ambitious
                  target.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use the numbers in your discussion or salary increase letter.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>How do I calculate my salary increase percentage?</h3>
              <p>Use the formula:</p>
              <p>
                \[ \text{Raise \%} = \frac{\text{New salary} - \text{Old
                salary}}{\text{Old salary}} \times 100 \]
              </p>
              <p>
                Or simply enter your old and new salary in the calculator and it
                will compute the percentage for you.
              </p>

              <h3>Is a 5% raise good?</h3>
              <p>
                In many organizations, a 3–5% raise is considered a solid annual
                increase for good performance. Whether 5% is “good” for you
                depends on:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Recent inflation and cost of living in your area.</li>
                <li>How your pay compares to market rates for your role.</li>
                <li>Your performance level and added responsibilities.</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>How often do companies give salary increases?</h3>
              <p>
                Many employers review salaries annually, often aligned with
                performance reviews or the fiscal year. Some also give off-cycle
                raises for promotions, role changes, or market adjustments.
              </p>

              <h3>Does this calculator include taxes?</h3>
              <p>
                No. The calculator works with <strong>gross pay</strong> (before
                tax and deductions). To estimate your new take-home pay, you can
                combine this tool with an income tax or paycheck calculator for
                your country or state.
              </p>
